5dLQLRzcjGfQ-j6dI7JctA.text: The Wet Fish Cafe has a friendly relaxed atmosphere. I like it for three different experiences: comforting brunch with the family, a contemplative hour on my own with a hot chocolate, or stylish dining out at night. One of the highlights of West Hampstead.

2KA5v7f4wUTkGjo13kuruA.text: I really like this place. They do one of the best capuccino's i've had in London and the food is pretty good. I lived in West Hampstead previously and I frequented here. Most of the time it was just for coffee (they make capucinno's like the Italians do) but i've also had breakfast and lunch here. The food is pretty good, although not fantastic. The staff are usually pretty friendly and there's quite a nice relaxed ambience to the place. If you're passing and you fancy a coffee, give it a blast. Also for a nice lunch or realxed dinner I'd recommend this place.

BflyTKTFbrnsebBVzNYwkw.text: Oooh Wet Fish... you left me wanting more!I tried The Wet Fish with a few friends.  We arrived early and were able to get in on the "Happy Hour"-esq Early Bird (4-7 PM, return your table by 8 PM) meal option of starter and main item for £15 each.  I tried the crispy squid which was quite tasteless.  Then I had the steak au poivre w rosemary sautéed potatoes & spinach salad.  Sadly the spinach salad was the most tasteful item on my plate and that is probably because of the salad dressing.  My friends tried the prawn moqueca (stew) w coconut milk, palm oil, peppers & rice (she sent hers back as it was slightly cold and not good) and the cod pan-fried w roast new potatoes, samphire and lemon & garlic butter (new potatoes were decent, cod wasn't good).I probably won't be making a trip back to The Wet Fish.  Sorry, but I prefer flavor with my meal!(Also, I must note that their toilet was less than acceptable as it wasn't clean, half of the toilet paper was wet and you probably will spend about 5 minutes searching for the flush - it's high above the toilet to your right... almost invisible.)

t0eG2B7Zqndd1iCoV-Tj2Q.text: Like other reviewers, I've passed by this restaurant several times and thought it had the most unfortunate name.  A friend of mine had heard wonderful things about the restaurant and as a result of her pestering, we went for dinner.  The interior brings you to a small restaurant in the countryside of France.  It feels like a place that only locals would know existed.  We all had the most delicious dinners -- I had salmon which sounds pretty boring but it was divine.  We also enjoyed a lovely thyme infused cheesecake and the most amazing chocolate cake.  I will definitely visit the Wet Fish again.

Dlz829nfJcOpHzfH3owaKQ.text: They were very friendly. They gave me a fresh ginger tea with lemon. Delicious. One of the best teas I've ever had and I got an amazing vegetarian meal there. So yummy! Staff is super friendly and relaxed.

G5V3w17O0CZR5Iaunq2f0g.text: The Wet Fish cafe has some of the best hot chocolate I've encountered in my travels. Sadly, it also has some of the least responsive staff I've bumped into. They're not rude, just fashionably aloof.Luckily carefully turned out daily lunch special for 6 pounds, inviting leather seats and power outlets for working lunches and fresh avacado smoothies keep me coming back, week after week.

-0Ez4JGkhy1f638CwOrDnQ.text: Awesome food.  I loved the combination of fish and chorizo.  Service was a tad bit slow.

JE_raZwH3yiIHNj_edpY-A.text: This a nice fish cafe. I like coming here for lunch and now they have an amazing offer  lunch for only 7 gbp  that's a deal, isn't it? Place is classy but on it's way cosy. I like going there also for a formal dinner. Food is just delicious and their desserts are mmm Really nice place.

lhBXTdY6PFMeETU_guC3hg.text: I'm ashamed to admit it, but it took me ages to go anywhere near this place. Thought it was primarily a fish restaurant and always walked by without looking at the menu (I know very daft of me!) However after perusing the menu I found this place to be an ideal brunch spot for those Sunday morning hangovers! First class service, delicious food and a buzzy environment, would recommend it to everyone!

CbpXlvJ6AwDyW-cH6XXeNw.text: I was very hungover when I came to the Wet Fish Cafe in West Hampsted, so I was a little concerned by the name. Well, it concerned my sensitive stomach. Name aside, this is a perfect place to clean away the cobwebs of a Saturday night.This little cafe is charming, quirky and informal and when my friend and I came in for breakfast, we found it full of locals. So full that it was quite hard to get a table for our breakfast, but at least I knew that it had a good reputation.The menu is Modern European. This means plenty of fish, and plenty of sharing plates. We were here for brunch, so I ordered the Smoked Salmon and Scrambled Eggs. They were the creamiest eggs that I have had in a long time, and the portion was so big that I couldn't finish it.My friend had the French Toast. While mine was a savoury pick up, I couldn't resist tearing at his sweet dish. I thought mine tasted the best, but his was almost as good.I was jealous for everyone in West Hampsted having this little gem on their doorstep; it obviously is one of the locals in the know choices.

3V2poMFmlNBNVlndCROS2A.text: I've just moved into the neighbourhood and was quite excited about discovering a new brunch spot on the weekend with a friend. We settled on Wet Fish Cafe out of the various options on West End Lane because of its super-cool website, quirky interior and all-round rave reviews. We didn't however think we were signing up for a kindergarten nostalgia session, which is what we experienced at the hands of our Waitress Not Having a Good Day who took it upon herself to reform us errant children. So we asked for the specials of the day and WNHGD tells us they're on the board outside which left us a bit dumb-founded as we're inside. Helpfully, she clarified at the end of the meal when we asked her what that was about that she expected us to get up and go read the specials on the board outside! Anyway, that was followed by her interrupting our sentences before we could finish them and then telling us off for trying to change something on an order (friend didn't want the pancetta) "I already told you you couldn't do that....".  Real shame as the food was quite delicious (totally second the other recommendation on the potato scramble with re-fried beans, genius!), the other waitress serving the floor perfectly nice and helpful (she brought in the specials board for her tables) and the general ambience friendly and welcoming. To be fair, I called the owner the next day and he apologised profusely and I believe genuinely for our treatment at the hands of his staff and did not make any excuses for WNHGD's behaviour. But I would have liked an apology from her herself when I had raised the appalling service issues with her at the end of the meal rather than a dismissive shrug of the shoulders and a "there you go". Hoping it's a one-off and the owner did his best to reassure me that that's what it was but too scarred to give it another go just yet.

jAUIVb7ylhvK44TBqwFSQg.text: I might be a bit biased here as a good friend is the head chef at this restaurant but i have to say i had one of the best steaks in London at the Wet Fish Cafe The restaurant is a great place to eat as the kitchen floats above the bar with a small window visible to see Will the chef at work. I followed the meal with a few coffees and even those were fntastic as shapes were produced in the frothy top. I will def be returning again.

NQP2Upw9L2GD2X3majLnYA.text: The Wet Fish Café is the result of an excellent renovation job a few years back: strip back the old plastering, and reveal the wonderful glazed tiles of what used to be a fresh fish shop. It's now one of my favourite places for a weekend brunch. It's not huge, so you may need to wait for one of the dozen or so tables. It's a great spot full of locals, though. The food has a touch of the fancy about it, and a whole lot of taste. The French toast is great, as is the scrambled eggs with chorizo and refried beans, and the bacon on polenta. There's a full menu for other mealtimes too, so if you're after more than breakfast with coffee you've got plenty of choice. There are usually a few newspapers around, too.

lOIc6LJJ8L1CoKeWOFgfoA.text: A good place to enjoy in the afternoon or during the week as it is usually quieter than at the week end or so I hear.We go there to enjoy a cafe-croissant and maybe a ciggie on the small terrace outside, looking at the passers-by and possibly change the world for the better with a couple of friends.It has got a good atmosphere, a bit like the french cafes and they have good food for fairly reasonnable prices. The waiters are laid-back and helpful so it is a nice spot to go to if you are in the area.

wB_KI_qFmVOV-As9XDCZ3A.text: Great place to spend a lazy Sunday catching up with an old friend. The setting is cute, ecclectic and casual - just like the menu! Their brunch menu is available from 10-4, the ideal window for brunch if you ask me! The chorizo, potato scramble served with black beans and salad was amazing as was the strawberry and banana smoothie with milk. The prices and service are decent. It's worth a repeat visit!

nje5Q1VKhhPsaUyNV0UTZA.text: Probably the best place for a lazy Sunday brunch in West Hampstead. It's a little pricey, but the food is fresh and attentively prepared. Try the bubble and squeak or scrambled eggs.

cRc-K0SCMhouMiuTXzIoUA.text: A great brunch spot. Probably the best coffee in West Hampstead. Dishes are very simple and fresh and rely heavily on the quality of the ingredients.

VrMc4R5ItuaNIhNH6POF1A.text: A real winner of a cafe in a cracking location. My friend introduced me to it on a rare sunny day and I was happy to sit outside, tucking into smoked salmon and scrambled eggs on taost which, as always, was a winner. We followed this up with a tasty plate of all kinds of titbits including dates, cheese, chorizo and prawns, all washed down with some minted lemonade. All in all I would highly recommend this place to anyone passing by as I think it offers great food, friendly staff and a nice, relaxed atmosphere.

c0qzyf9jvlGsENdyY7X3cg.text: Really cute quirky decor! They do the best breakfasts in West Hampstead and I also recommend their lattes. Good friendly service, but quite pricey.

rNv5gIZZkzEBtMnHSdrwrw.text: Wet Fish is a West Hampstead gem. I feel so lucky to live close to a restaurant that serves brunch, lunch and dinner with a consistent view on quality. The atmosphere is sophisticated, but not at all snobby.

5CSIKZmiuQuhRMJMKJHitg.text: Good brunch place in W Hampstead. Getting a bit too popular now, with the service suffering a little, but the food and coffee is good. Try the French toast!

SjdMZ5KPxwLwtEyDnNVKRQ.text: Went along for one of their music nights; Natalie Duncan was performing (who was fantastic by the way). Overall it was a very good experience in a cute, romantic and intimate space with good food elevated by amazing service. They use the limited space very well and never felt cramped in there. There's also plenty to look at on the walls with (what I think) was art available to purchase. Due to the entertainment and layout I wasn't able to check it all out but what I saw looked interesting, particularly the neon river above the bar. The set menu for the evening was tremendous value at £29.50. I ordered the scallops and salmon whilst my partner had the cod terrine and lamb. All the dishes were solid options, good portion size and well presented. We also had a couple of cocktails and I enjoyed the Negroni. What would make me return to this place was the service. From the warm welcome to the sincere thank you as we left everything was exceptional. Service was prompt and they handled the quietness of the room when Natalie was performing with the respect it deserved. They were happy to recommend dishes, were attentive and friendly throughout. Overall I would recommend the entertainment nights wholeheartedly and will be back in the future.

rkQJevcnQH_exsDokS3Gkw.text: The Wet Fish is almost always excellent, but it depends what time of day you arrive. Saturdays are packed with hungry Whampstead brunchers and you'll be lucky to grab a table (when you do, expect perfectly good if slightly-too-pricey eggs in various forms). It's much more enjoyable in the odd between bit when they've stopped lunch and haven't quite started dinner service. The service is better, you can get the best tables by the window and it's all a little less... rushed.Order the hot chocolate, it's thick and laced with nutmeg. Take a good book, you're going to want to stay a while.

xpOO3JrtinAV-ix12n1WuA.text: I did like the place, the atmosphere and the food.Good service (very nice) I ordered the "hungover cure" (scramble eggs w/ chorizo, potatoes, black beans, salad + bloody Mary + coffe. Everithing was OK except the bloody Mary (if you like it, try it though, I'm not a big fan of it but I wanted to try it). Next time I will try something sweet like French toast. Spanish speakers: es un lugar agradable en West Hampstead. Lo recomiendo si vivis cerca de West End Lane. El rango de precios varía entre £8 y £16. Si no os convence el bloody mary, no os lo recomiendo, si estais con resaca es una bomba!

photos.caption: Photo of The Wet Fish Cafe & Brasserie - London, United Kingdom. the hungover cure

uUPc1SsOQ8jwT67iWuZwyQ.text: This is the kind of brunch place that I really miss.  It reminds me of being in Chicago - a menu with drink options from green smoothies to Bloody Marys, and creative cuisine of both the healthy and "comfort food" persuasion.  We didn't struggle to get seated at noon on a Sunday, though nearly every table was full.  It is a bit noisy in there, just filled up with trendy twenty-and-thirty somethings, and the servers are rushing around you.  While it isn't perhaps a place to sit and relax quietly on a weekend, you will get a great brunch that will surely cure your hangover.We shared a green smoothie which was very nice and creamy, no doubt from the avocado.  Loved the mango flavor.  Then we got bubble and squeak, and a potato-chorizo-egg scramble.  Both were great - loved the spicy chorizo which went so well with the black beans alongside.  The eggs were very delicate and fluffy, which I often find isn't the case in restaurants.  The bubble and squeak was great too - poached eggs and a big cake made of potatoes, mushrooms, and various other veggies.  Neither portion was enormous (we had a mid-day snack later) but I loved not feeling too full and gross afterwards.  We don't come to Hampstead often, but I'd eat here again anytime we were in the area!

ymsfVH6xzOXT-JOxIfoXOA.text: High quality produce cooked very well!  Always a pleasure to visit this romantic restaurant...

CW2IbALv1XqWesopSnvfcA.text: Went here to try the fish and wow was I pleased with what they served. I had the classic battered haddock but it came with a twist of potato cooked in soy sauce and spinach on the side. It was delicious! The fish was perfect and potato tasted so well on the tongue. My boyfriend had the fish special of the day and the fish was seasoned so perfectly with Indian spices and it came with cooked beetroot on the side which was also wonderful. Book your place before you come in because the place is not so big and dinner is surely always busy here.

FOe9akPtucqA1zKHhfpo_A.text: Nice ambience , great food. We had the eggs west hampstead and the bubble and squeak. Both dishes were really nice. Will definitely come back. Minor downside, it took slightly longer than expected to get the food, but then again, it is better to have slow good food than rushed mediocre one.

TndmM2LYmV9Nu-l93-fKcQ.text: Brunch heaven, this place is.Visited with three other friends at 10 am on a rainy Saturday morning, and each of us got something different. The original plan was to share, but I think everyone enjoyed their own plates so much that no actual sharing took place. All the dishes looked very good, and the smoothies are a must try.I got the potato, chorizo, and eggs scramble - and though it didn't look like a healthy portion when the food came out, it was very filling and very good - just the right amount. I would highly recommended it.Another thing I would recommend is to come early (as close to open as possible). When we got there, the place had maybe 3-4 tables full. By 10:45 am, there were was a queue of people and baby strollers. I can see why this place would get busy - great food at good prices in a relaxed atmosphere.Will definitely be back - maybe I'll see you if you come in at the open on Saturdays.

TF8DkHwerqUb8hWYksSxSg.text: Lovely little place - it was comfortable and cozy and had great service! Went for brunch - I enjoyed my scramble with chorizo and potatoes. We went right when they opened and beat the rush!

LYIfMkt9Gc06AsAmx_uoJg.text: I came in for brunch and was very impressed with this little cafe.  It still has some remnants of its past as an old fishmongers and it's very charming and cozy.   I got the hangover special, which is a lovely Bloody Mary, a coffee and a chorizo and potato scramble for £16.  Just the perfect thing to start the day.  Breakfast is served late and there looked to be many other things I would like to try.   I can't wait to go back!

Za2F2J4D4mPgHy3gGbeIlQ.text: One word for this place - solid!No downs but no real ups either. Good brunch selection and "post hangover" food. Atmosphere is trendy-local, young and crowded( but the friendly staff always found us a table)

IOMHae2g5ZK5qDxUGmpudQ.text: The Wet Fish Cafe is a place for idealists. I mean this in the most positive way, as this place strives for more than just a place where you can eat something. You get great food by people who love food. The atmosphere is nice and you isnatntly see and feel that this place isn't a generic business but a restaurant run by real people with a love for what they do.Anthing that you eat in here deserves a 5star rating. Truly one of the best places in West Hampstead.

0Ml3yeV5-WiEsmbCf3TjpQ.text: Good buzzy atmosphere, and the place definitely has character. Got the breakfast salad and it was tasty, well cooked eggs and flavourful dressing, but it wasn't quite what I expected based on the menu description, which my friends also found with their meals. Overall decent food and friendly service, but overpriced compared to other options around.

photos.caption: Photo of The Wet Fish Cafe & Brasserie - London, United Kingdom. Breakfast Salad

cUEWLEQeFsV1V8YCI7h8zw.text: We visited the Wet Fish Café for Saturday brunch. The table ordered the following:* potato, chorizo and egg scramble - The chorizo had  a  great, spicy flavour that infused the eggs. The eggs themselves were expertly cooked, meaning that it hit the balance of being fully cooked without being nuked and dried.  The toast and potatoes were both nice; although, I think one or the other would be enough starch for me.I can't opine on the refried beans as the person who ordered this dish requested NO BEANS.  One observation, they do not appear to be refried. * scrambled eggs w home-cured gravadlax, avocado, cream cheese & toast - Again the eggs were perfectly cooked.  I believe chives were mixed into the eggs which was a nice addition.  Not sure what the cured gravadlax (my first ever) was supposed to taste like, but it tasted like a mixture of lox, sashimi and ceviche - not a bad mixture if you ask me!* Americano  - only available in one (smallish) size* Flat white - only available in one (smallish) sizeHighly recommend for the cool, laid back neighbourhood café vibe and simple, well executed food.    Also, given the quality and service, the meal was a good value. All in, we left for £24.

GpF-fD7MRdJbQqVaOTBpgA.text: The food was real good! Though the courses were little small, but the service is great and the place is beautiful

UFQEXQ7nFVZ8nFWIioH6Kg.text: It feels slightly partisan but we still had some room. The service is always friendly. I just came here for a little snack of muesli and fruit. This was well served but appeared to be quite minimal. The fruit wasn't the tastiest and was limited to apples mainly. The yoghurt was also not the tastiest, although maybe it was meant to be plain. Although appears to be q favourite for more breakfast menus, this restaurant never quite ticks all my boxes.

MA_4mpIM6kdwq71HH0DuCg.text: Good coffee, however the food is hit and miss. I've been going here for 5 years and am afraid that the consistance is off the mark. Also, the menu never changes much which is a shame.

TDrHhQnWP-yrtXxzWONt7g.text: We didn't have to wait on a Saturday which is a huge plus.The menu was no frills, but well executed. The food quality was above average, and a mixture between british/american choices. I enjoyed my breakfast, but wish it has a bit more panache. If possible I would have given this place 3.5 stars. That being said, I would definitely stop back here someday.The hot cocoa is good according to my friend.:3

o1-m3Eq8nr_2HFU-VWmAhA.text: I love the epic lunch deals here. Coffee and brunch for £6, could life get any better?

BgfQfHDNDLf2NMMJTsCHRQ.text: Cute place, good service, and the eggs benedict was savage. What more could you ask for on a saturday morning?
